od: Perspectives on Romans 3:2 in Light of the Old Testament -- tChapter 13. A Synopsis of Galatians and Romans: Its Relevance for the Interpretation of the Synoptic Parallels between 1 and 2 Thessalonians and between Colossians and Ephesians -- tChapter 14. “Or is God the God of Jews Only?” (Rom 3:29a): The Renewal of the Covenant at the Last Supper and the Inclusion of Gentiles -- tChapter 15. Circumcision and Baptism? Aphrahat’s Demonstrations as a Window to Jewish Initiation in Persia -- tChapter 16. Leading the Righteous: Leadership and Privilege in the Light of Romans 3 -- tChapter 17. “Let God Be True Though Every One Were a Liar” (Rom 3:4): Speech Ethics in Romans 3 -- tChapter 18. On Not Knowing the Truth and Being Committed to It -- tIndices0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRomans 3 contains exegetically stormy waters, where even the most capable interpreters may feel at sea. In this book, an international group of scholars put their oars into these choppy waters, shedding new light on this wonderful and complex passage of Scripture. The focused and methodologically varied approach allows for greater depth of research than is generally possible in commentaries. Specialists on Romans, especially Romans 3, will find in this book a wealth of information. Likewise, it will be of value to students in advanced exegetical classes and those doing postgraduate research on Romans 3 and related topics. This book is dedicated to Prof. Dr. Martin Webber on his 70th birthday.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aBible. 4aReligion. 4aStudy/NewTestament. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Studies / New Testament.2bisacsh1 aBarentsen, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaum, Armin D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.